content.title: Lets Get started with Github Learning...
subtitle: Learn how to start building, collaborating and maintaning software over github, You can use GitHub and Git to collaborate on work.
difference1: Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes in code.
It allows developers to manage branches, merge changes, and revert to previous versions.
Git works locally on your computer and does not require an internet connection.
It helps in maintaining a history of code changes and supports collaboration when pushed to a remote repository.
difference2: GitHub is a cloud-based platform for hosting Git repositories.
It allows multiple developers to collaborate on a project by using pull requests and forks.
GitHub provides additional features like issue tracking, code reviews, and project management.
It requires authentication and provides access control for private and public repositories.

To start using Git in a new or existing project, navigate to your project folder and initialize it as a Git repository.
This creates a hidden .git directory that stores repository data.

content.title: Git Status
subtitle: The `git status` command displays the state of the working directory and the staging area.
It shows which changes have been staged, which haven't, and which files aren't being tracked by Git.
This command helps you understand what changes need to be committed.

commands.step: Step 1: Check the status of your repository
expected_output: Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'.
(use 'git add <file>...' to update what will be committed)
(use 'git restore <file>...' to discard changes in working directory)
(use 'git add <file>...' to include in what will be committed)
output_explanation: On branch main : Shows the current branch.
Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main' : Indicates that your local branch matches the remote branch.
Changes to be committed : Lists files that have been staged (ready for commit).
Changes not staged for commit : Shows modified files that haven't been added to staging.
Untracked files : Lists files that are new and not yet tracked by Git.

links.name: Git Basics - Checking Status of Files

content.title: Git Add
subtitle: The `git add` command adds changes in the working directory to the staging area.
It is used to prepare changes before committing them.
Files must be staged using `git add` before they can be committed.
After running these commands, `git status` will show the staged files under 'Changes to be committed'.

commands.step: 1: Add a specific file to the staging area
2: Add all changes (modified, new, and deleted files) to the staging area

links.name: Git Basics - Tracking Files with Git Add

content.title: Git Commit
subtitle: The `git commit` command saves changes from the staging area to the local repository.
Each commit represents a snapshot of the project at a specific point in time.
Commits include a message that describes the changes made.

commands.step: Step 1: Commit staged changes with a message
Step 2: Commit all changes (including unstaged files) directly
output_explanation: [main 1a2b3c4] Your commit message : Indicates that the commit was made on the `main` branch, with a unique commit hash (`1a2b3c4`).
2 files changed, 10 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-) : Shows how many files were modified and the number of lines added/removed.

content.title: Git Log
subtitle: The `git log` command displays the commit history of the repository.
It shows details such as commit hash, author, date, and commit message.
This command helps track changes and understand the project's history.

commands.step: Step 1: View the commit history
expected_output: Added a new feature to improve performance
Fixed a bug in authentication logic
output_explanation: commit abc1234def5678ghijklmnop : The unique identifier (hash) of the commit.
(HEAD -> main, origin/main) : Indicates that this is the latest commit on the `main` branch.
Author: John Doe <john.doe@example.com> : Displays who made the commit.
Date: Mon Mar 11 10:30:00 2024 +0530 : Shows when the commit was made.
Added a new feature to improve performance : The commit message describing the changes.

links.name: Git Basics - Viewing Commit History with Git Log

content.title: Branch Creation and Listing
subtitle: Git branches allow you to create separate lines of development within the same repository.
Branches are useful for working on new features, bug fixes, or experiments without affecting the main codebase.
You can create, list, and switch between branches using Git commands.

commands.step: Step 1: Create a new branch
output_explanation: This command creates a new branch but does not switch to it.
The branch is created based on the current HEAD.

commands.step: Step 2: Create a new branch and switch to it
output_explanation: This is equivalent to `git branch <branch-name>` followed by `git checkout <branch-name>`.
It creates the branch and immediately switches to it.

commands.step: Step 3: List all branches
output_explanation: * main : The asterisk (*) indicates the currently active branch.
Other branches are listed without an asterisk.

content.title: Switching Between Branches
subtitle: Switching branches allows you to work on different lines of development.
Git ensures that your working directory reflects the state of the branch you switch to.
Uncommitted changes may prevent switching if they conflict with the target branch.

commands.step: Step 1: Switch to an existing branch
output_explanation: This command switches to the specified branch.
The working directory is updated to match the state of the branch.

content.title: Merging Branches
subtitle: Merging combines changes from one branch into another.
Typically, you merge feature branches into the main branch when the work is complete.
Git performs fast-forward merges when possible, or creates a merge commit for non-linear history.

commands.step: Step 1: Merge a branch into the current branch
output_explanation: Updating abc1234..def5674 : Shows the range of commits being merged.
Fast-forward : Indicates a fast-forward merge (if possible).
File changes are listed, showing insertions and deletions.

commands.step: Step 2: Merge with a commit (non-fast-forward)
output_explanation: --no-ff : Forces a merge commit, even if fast-forward is possible.
This preserves the branch history in the commit graph.

content.title: Handling Merge Conflicts
subtitle: Merge conflicts occur when Git cannot automatically reconcile changes from two branches.
Conflicts must be resolved manually before completing the merge.
Git marks conflicting sections in the affected files for resolution.

commands.step: Step 1: Check merge conflict status
output_explanation: `You have unmerged paths`: Indicates a merge conflict.
`both modified: app.js`: Lists files with conflicts.

commands.step: Step 2: Resolve conflicts in files, then stage them
output_explanation: After manually resolving conflicts in the file, stage it with `git add`.
This marks the conflict as resolved.

commands.step: Step 3: Complete the merge
output_explanation: Completes the merge by creating a merge commit.
Git automatically generates a merge commit message.

content.title: Deleting Branches
subtitle: Once a branch is merged or no longer needed, you can delete it.
Deleting branches helps keep the repository clean and manageable.
Be cautious when deleting unmerged branches, as their changes may be lost.

commands.step: Step 1: Delete a merged branch
output_explanation: -d : Deletes the branch only if it has been merged.
Git will prevent deletion if the branch has unmerged changes.

commands.step: Step 2: Force delete an unmerged branch
output_explanation: -D : Force deletes the branch, even if it has unmerged changes.
Use with caution, as unmerged changes will be lost.

content.title: Creating the Pull Request
subtitle: A Pull Request (PR) is a request to merge changes from one branch to another in a version control system like Git. It allows developers to propose, review, and collaborate on code changes before merging them into the main project.

details: Step 1: Complete Your Work on a Feature Branch
Before creating a pull request, ensure that you have completed your changes on a separate feature branch. A feature branch helps keep changes isolated and makes collaboration easier.
Step 2: Push Your Changes to GitHub
Once you’ve made and committed all necessary changes, push your feature branch to the remote repository on GitHub.
Step 3: Go to Your Repository on GitHub
GitHub will detect the recently pushed branch and display a prompt suggesting you create a pull request. Click on the 'Compare & pull request' button.
Step 4: Compare Changes and Select Branches
Ensure that you are comparing the correct branches. The base branch should be the target branch (e.g., 'main' or 'develop'), and the compare branch should be your feature or bug-fix branch.
Step 5: Fill in the PR Details
Enter a title and description for your pull request
Step 6: Add Reviewers, Labels, and Projects

Before submitting your pull request, assign appropriate reviewers who will review your changes. Additionally, add relevant labels and link the PR to related projects or issues to provide better context.
Step 7 : Click on the 'Create pull request' button to submit your pull request for review.

content.title: Reviewing a Pull Request
subtitle: Reviewing a pull request involves checking the proposed changes, leaving comments, and approving or requesting modifications.
This ensures code quality and consistency before merging.

details: Step 1: Navigate to the Pull Requests Section
Go to the repository on GitHub and click on the 'Pull Requests' tab to view the list of open pull requests.
Step 2: Select the Pull Request
Choose the pull request you want to review by clicking on its title. This will open the pull request details page.
Step 3: Review the Changes
Check the 'Files changed' tab to see the modifications. Review the code for correctness, readability according to coding standards.
Step 4: Add Comments or Suggestions
Use the GitHub inline commenting feature to provide feedback on specific lines of code. Leave general comments if needed.
Step 5: Approve or Request Changes
If the changes are good, approve the pull request. If improvements are needed, request changes and provide clear instructions.
Step 6: Merge the Pull Request (If Authorized)
If you have merge permissions and the changes are approved, merge the pull request into the main branch.
